n 1959.\n\nThe following table gives a preview of total number of registered people employed in legal entities per their core activity (as of 2018):<ref name=\"stats2018\">{{cite web |title=Cities and Municipalities of Republika Srpska |url=http://www2.rzs.rs.ba/static/uploads/bilteni/gradovi_i_opstine_republike_srpske/2019/Gradovi_I_Opstine_Republike_Srpske_2019_WEB.pdf |website=rzs.rs.ba |publisher=Republika Srspka Institute of Statistics |accessdate=31 December 2019 |format=PDF |date=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|-\n! Activity\n! Total\n|-\n|Agriculture, forestry and fishing||align=\"right\"|59\n|-\n|Mining and quarrying||align=\"right\"|870\n|-\n|Manufacturing||align=\"right\"|341\n|-\n|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply||align=\"right\"|23\n|-\n|Water supply; sewerage, waste management and remediation activities||align=\"right\"|30\n|-\n|Construction||align=\"right\"|14\n|-\n|Wholesale and retail trade, repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles||align=\"right\"|113\n|-\n|Transportation and storage||align=\"right\"|73\n|-\n|Accommodation and food services||align=\"right\"|32\n|-\n|Information and communication||align=\"right\"|10\n|-\n|Financial and insurance activities||align=\"right\"|40\n|-\n|Real estate activities||align=\"right\"|-\n|-\n|Professional, scientific and technical activities||align=\"right\"|23\n|-\n|Administrative and support service activities||align=\"right\"|5\n|-\n|Public administration and defense; compulsory social security||align=\"right\"|115\n|-\n|Education||align=\"right\"|128\n|-\n|Human health and social work activities||align=\"right\"|56\n|-\n|Arts, entertainment and recreation||align=\"right\"|11\n|-\n|Other service activities||align=\"right\"|14\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n|'''Total'''||align=\"right\"|'''1,957'''\n|}\n\n==Sports==\nThe local football team, [[FK Boksit Mili\u0107i]], were also established by the company in 1972.\n\nIn the 1990s, businessman Rajko Duki\u0107 invested in sports development in Mili\u0107i, and local teams became champions of Republika Srpska in football, chess, bowling and women's handball. He also invested in a large cultural complex occupying the centre of the town, including a museum, motel, pool complex and the 65-metre tall 'Rajko's Tower'.<ref>http://lat.rtrs.tv/vijesti/vijest/miliciotvoren-toranj-i-muzej-rudarstva-13146</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Municipalities of Republika Srpska]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* Official results from the book ''Ethnic composition of Bosnia-Herzegovina population, by municipalities and settlements, 1991''. Census, Zavod za statistiku Bosne i Hercegovine - Bilten no.234, Sarajevo 1991.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mili\u0107i}}\n\n{{Political divisions of Bosnia and Herzegovina}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Mili\u0107i, Republika Srpska]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Republika Srpska]]\n\n{{Mili\u0107i-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "EcLiPsE285", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mili%C4%87i,_Republika_Srpska"}
{"title_page": "KoreKorea", "text_new": "[[File:Loading copra at Betio port, Kiribati.JPG |250px|thumb|right|KoreKorea engage in sex with the crews of foreign fishing vessels berthed at [[Betio]] wharf.<ref name=\"Harborow\">Harborow, H. The Pacific's Hidden Trade. UNICEF. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://www.unicef.org/pacificislands/reallives_2966.html link]</ref>]]\n'''KoreKorea''' was a term used for girls in [[Kiribati]] who Korean fishermen paid for sex.<ref name=\"Hankyoreh\">The Shame in 'KoreKorea'. (2005). The Hankyoreh. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://legacy.www.hani.co.kr/section-001100000/2005/07/001100000200507090244001.html link]</ref> They are now called '''ainen matawa''' locally \"''in deference to Korean sensitivities''\", because the word \"''Korekorea''\" was overtly linked to the \"''principal nationality of their clients''\".<!--This information is in the first paragraph of the right column of numbered page 3 which is the fifth page of the PDF document. The source text indicated that \"ainen matawa\" is the term that they are now called with the statement \"Korekore... was dropped from official usage, and consequently common parlance\".--><ref name=Risky/> The girls are around the age of eighteen and are even as young as fourteen years old.<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 Trafficking in Persons Report - Kiribati |publisher=United States Department of State / UNHCR |date=19 June 2012 |url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=country&category=&publisher=&type=&coi=KIR&rid=45b632e02&docid=4fe30cba48&skip=0}}</ref><ref name=\"FFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ffa.int/system/files//home/ffaadmin//files/ffa/Gender%20issues%20in%20P.I.%20tuna%20industries%20II%20.pdf |title=Sullivan, N. & Ram-Bidesi, V. (2008). Gender Issues in Tuna Fisheries Case Studies in Papua New Guinea, Fiji and Kiribati. |accessdate=2017-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220191528/http://www.ffa.int/system/files//home/ffaadmin//files/ffa/Gender%20issues%20in%20P.I.%20tuna%20industries%20II%20.pdf |archivedate=February 20, 2011 }}</ref> They board foreign fishing vessels and engage in sex in exchange for money, clothes and fish.<ref name=\"Risky\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fsm.ac.fj/files/Risky%20Bussiness%20Kiribati-%20HIV%20prevention%20amongst%20women%20who%20board.pdf |title=McMillan K., and H. Worth (2010) Risky Business Kiribati: HIV prevention amongst women who board foreign fishing vessels to sell sex. International HIV Research Group, UNSW, Sydney. |accessdate=2013-06-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030210044/http://www.fsm.ac.fj/files/Risky%20Bussiness%20Kiribati-%20HIV%20prevention%20amongst%20women%20who%20board.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"CSEC\">Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children (CSEC) and Child Sexual Abuse (CSA) in the Pacific: A Regional Report. (2006). UNICEF Pacific. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://www.unicef.org/eapro/Pacific_CSEC_report.pdf link]</ref>\n\n==Awareness==\nA 2005 news article in [[The Korea Times]] said that, according to [[ECPAT]]-Korea, \"''te korekorea''\" are \"''the best known cases of commercial sexual exploitation of children''\".<!--This information is in the fifth paragraph that starts with \"According to the children's\". The \"children's advocate group\" mentioned in the fifth paragraph is \"ECPAT-Korea\" which is mentioned in the third paragraph and not the \"National Youth Commission\" which is mentioned in the first paragraph. The second, sixth, eighth, ninth and tenth paragraphs mention \"the commission\" which is how the news article refers to the \"National Youth Commission\" after its name was introduced, so the \"children's advocate group\" refers to \"ECPAT-Korea\" of the third paragraph.--><ref name=\"CheongWon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=2665523 |title=Kim, C. (2005). Korean Fishermen Blamed for Child Sex Trade in Kiribati. The Korea Times. |accessdate=2016-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191647/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=2665523 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Countries involved==\n===Involvement of Kiribati===\nA 2006 news article in [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] said that \"''all Korean fishing boats''\" had been banned by Kiribati from going to Kiribati's ports for a time in 2003 following reports in [[The Korea Herald]] \"''that 30 to 50 girls, mostly under age, were servicing the Korean fishermen.''\"<!--This information is in the fifth paragraph from the bottom that starts with \"He confirms that the situation\".--><ref>Tiniest nations caught in a net. (2006). The Sydney Morning Herald. Retrieved November 25, 2016, from [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2006/10/08/1160246011151.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap3 link]</ref>\n\nThe KoreKorea issue is being addressed by a Korean institution in collaboration with the Kiribati Government cooperating with the ILO Youth unemployment programme and with the New Zealand's International Aid and Development Agency (NZAID).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ilo.org/declaration/follow-up/annualreview/archiveofbaselinesbycountry/WCMS_DECL_CL_KIR/lang--en/index.htm |title=Kiribati - Country baselines under the ILO Declaration Annual Review (2000-2008): Effective abolition of child labour \n|publisher=International Labour Organization |date= 15 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Involvement of South Korea===\nA 2005 news article in [[The Korea Times]] said that the National Youth Commission would try to get the \"''Korean fishermen''\" punished as South Korea's \"''anti-juvenile-prostitution law''\" did not allow for \"''sex trade''\".<!--This information is in the third paragraph from the bottom that starts with \"As the anti-juvenile-prostitution\". The \"commission\" mentioned in that paragraph is the \"National Youth Commission\" mentioned in the first paragraph.--><ref name=\"CheongWon\" />\n\n==Mixed children==\nA 2005 news article in [[The Hankyoreh]] said that children had been made from \"''Some''\" \"''KoreKorea''\" and \"''Korean fishermen''\".<ref name=\"Hankyoreh\" />\n\nA 2010 report made by the International HIV Research Group of the [[University of New South Wales]] said that children had been made from \"''a number''\" of ''ainen matawa''\" and \"''Korean seafarers''\", and the report said that the Korean fathers send financial support to these children.<!--This information is in the last sentence of the first paragraph of the right column of numbered page 9 which is the eleventh page of the PDF document.--><ref name=\"Risky\" />\n\n==Men who have sex with ainen matawa==\n===Condom use===\nA document named \"''Synthesis_Kiribati_2013''\"<!--The name of the document can be seen in the end of the URL address as \".../Synthesis_Kiribati_2013.pdf\" and also when a person tries to download the PDF document the default name upon confirming the download is \"Synthesis_Kiribati_2013\".--> on the [[Burnet Institute|Burnet Institute's]] website<!--The Burnet Institute's name and logo is at the bottom of every page of the PDF document and the root of the URL address for the PDF document is \"www.burnet.edu.au/...\".--> said that \"''condom use is intermittent''\" among the \"''ainen matawa''\".<!--The information about condom use is in the last paragraph of the right column of the first page.--><ref>Synthesis_Kiribati_2013. Burnet Institute. [https://www.burnet.edu.au/system/asset/file/992/Synthesis_Kiribati_2013.pdf link]</ref>\n\n==Ainen matawa==\n===Age of ainen matawa===\nA 2005 news article in [[The Hankyoreh]] said that the KoreKorea females were about 18 years old.<!--This is in the first paragraph that starts with \"There is a place where\".--><ref name=\"Hankyoreh\" />\n\nA 2006 report by [[UNICEF]] Pacific<!--This information is at the bottom of PDF page 3 to the right of the word \"Copyright\".--> said that \"''80 young te korekorea... had visited boats in port in 2000''\".<!--This quote is in the second sentence of the second paragraph that starts with \"The statistics obtained from police\" of PDF document page 49 which is numbered as page 34.--><ref name=\"CSEC\" />\n\nA 2007 news article in [[The Korea Times]] said that \"''te korekorea''\" were \"''teenage girls''\",<!--This is in the first paragraph.--> and 8 of 24 of the interviewed \"''te korekorea''\" were younger than 19 and one was 14 years old.<!--These numbers are in the third paragraph that starts with \"The commission interviewed\". The source material said that one-third of 24 women were younger than 19 which is equal to 8, since 24 divided by 3 equals 8.--> The news article also said that the age when \"''te korekorea''\" first start was \"''getting younger''\".<!--The starting age getting younger is in the sixth paragraph that starts with \"The commission estimated\". The term \"te korekorea\" is in the fifth paragraph that starts with \"In Kiribati, young sex workers\". The news article uses a longer description involving girls having sex with Korean sailors for money in Kiribati for most of the article when referring to \"te korekorea\", and the article only mentions the term \"te korekorea\" once to state that that is the term used there for such people, but the longer-description instances refer to the same \"te korekorea\" females. The repeated quotation of \"te korekorea\" here is used to indicate that the source material used the term \"te korekorea\" instead of the other term \"ainen matawa\" and not to indicate that the term \"te korekorea\" was used multiple times in the source material.--><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=3083017 |title=Rahn, K. (2007). Sailors Blamed for Child Sex Trade. The Korea Times. |accessdate=2016-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191544/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=3083017 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nA 2008 report by the [[Pacific Islands Forum]] Fisheries Agency<!--The agency's acronym \"FFA\" can be seen in the bottom-left of the first page of the PDF document. The base URL address of the PDF document was \"www.ffa.int\". The title at the top of the www.ffa.int website shows that the organization's name is \"Pacific Islands Forum Fisheries Agency (FFA)\". The date of the report is at the bottom of the second page of the PDF document.--> said that \"''Teenage girls from the outer islands''\" were the group who were \"''particularly vulnerable to becoming Te korekorea''\".<!--This information is in the second paragraph from the bottom of page 31 which starts with \"When parents have no income\".--><ref name=\"FFA\" />\n\nA 2010 report made by the International HIV Research Group of the [[University of New South Wales]] said that the \"''ainen matawa''\" were \"''young women''\".<!--The organization's name and the description of the women are in the second page in the paragraph under the title \"Acknowledgements\".--><ref name=\"Risky\" />\n\nA 2012 document made by the Kiribati Local Government Association<!--The first words at the top of page 2 say that it is produced by this association.--> explained the term \"''ainen matawa''\" with the words \"''teenage prostitution, involving very young girls''\".<!--This quote is from the first explained \"Kiribati Words\" at the bottom of page 4.--><ref>Strategic Plan 2012-2014. (2012). Kiribati Local Government Association. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://www.kilga.org.ki/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/KiLGAs-Strategic-Plan-approved-by-GM.pdf link]</ref>\n\nA web page on [[UNICEF]]'s website said that the \"''korekorea''\" were \"''young women''\".<!--This information is in the tenth paragraph from the bottom that starts with \"In Kiribati, young women\".--><ref name=\"Harborow\" />\n\n===Stigma of being ainen matawa===\nA 2013 document by the [[World Health Organization]] said that \"''ainen matawa''\" were inhibited from utilizing \"''sexual and reproductive health services''\", because of the \"''stigma, discrimination, violence and/or social exclusion''\" that they faced.<!--This information is in page number 3 which is the eleventh page of the PDF in the second paragraph which starts with \"While violence against women\".--><ref>Rasanathan, J.K. et al. <!--The authors of the document are mentioned in the sixth page of the PDF document which is page number \"iv\".-->(2013). Measuring and responding to violence against women in Kiribati: Action on gender inequality as a social determinant of health. World Health Organization: Western Pacific Region. Retrieved November 27, 2016, from [http://www.wpro.who.int/topics/gender/country_case_measuring_and_responding_to_gender-based_violence_kir.pdf link]</ref>\n\nA 2013 report on the [[United States Department of State|United States Department of State's]] website said that \"''ainen matawa''\" had a stigma within their society.<!--This information is in the last sentence of the first paragraph. The phrase \"their society\" is a rewording of the source text's phrase \"I-Kiribati society\".--><ref>2013 Trafficking in Persons Report. (2013). U.S. Department of State. Retrieved November 25, 2016, from [https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/tip/rls/tiprpt/countries/2013/215493.htm link]</ref>\n\nA 2014 report by [[WorldFish]] said that \"''ainen matawa''\" were \"''socially marginalized''\" for prostituting themselves, because what they were doing went against the values of their culture.<!--This information is in the second paragraph of the right column of numbered page 57 (PDF page 59) thatstarts with \"The increase in transshipment\". The phrase \"values of their culture\" is a rewording of the source text's phrase \"traditional and customary beliefs and principles\".--><ref>Campbell, B., Hanich, Q. (2014). Fish for the future: Fisheries development and food security for Kiribati in an era of global climate change. WorldFish, Penang, Malaysia. Project Report: 2014-47. Retrieved November 25, 2016, from [http://ro.uow.edu.au/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3440&context=lhapapers link]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Prostitution in Kiribati]]\n*[[Prostitution in South Korea]]\n*[[Lai \u0110\u1ea1i H\u00e0n]] Prostitution and rape by Korean soldiers in Vietnam\n*[[Kopino]] children of mixed Korean and Filipino descent to an unwed Filipina mother\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Child prostitution]]\n[[Category:Child sexual abuse]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Loading copra at Betio port, Kiribati.JPG |250px|thumb|right|KoreKorea engage in sex with the crews of foreign fishing vessels berthed at [[Betio]] wharf.<ref name=\"Harborow\">Harborow, H. The Pacific's Hidden Trade. UNICEF. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://www.unicef.org/pacificislands/reallives_2966.html link]</ref>]]\n'''KoreKorea''' was a term used for girls in [[Kiribati]] who Korean fishermen paid for sex.<ref name=\"Hankyoreh\">The Shame in 'KoreKorea'. (2005). The Hankyoreh. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://legacy.www.hani.co.kr/section-001100000/2005/07/001100000200507090244001.html link]</ref> They are now called '''ainen matawa''' locally \"''in deference to Korean sensitivities''\", because the word \"''Korekorea''\" was overtly linked to the \"''principal nationality of their clients''\".<!--This information is in the first paragraph of the right column of numbered page 3 which is the fifth page of the PDF document. The source text indicated that \"ainen matawa\" is the term that they are now called with the statement \"Korekore... was dropped from official usage, and consequently common parlance\".--><ref name=Risky/> The girls are around the age of eighteen and are even as young as fourteen years old.<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 Trafficking in Persons Report - Kiribati |publisher=United States Department of State / UNHCR |date=19 June 2012 |url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=country&category=&publisher=&type=&coi=KIR&rid=45b632e02&docid=4fe30cba48&skip=0}}</ref><ref name=\"FFA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ffa.int/system/files//home/ffaadmin//files/ffa/Gender%20issues%20in%20P.I.%20tuna%20industries%20II%20.pdf |title=Sullivan, N. & Ram-Bidesi, V. (2008). Gender Issues in Tuna Fisheries Case Studies in Papua New Guinea, Fiji and Kiribati. |accessdate=2017-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110220191528/http://www.ffa.int/system/files//home/ffaadmin//files/ffa/Gender%20issues%20in%20P.I.%20tuna%20industries%20II%20.pdf |archivedate=February 20, 2011 }}</ref> They board foreign fishing vessels and engage in sex in exchange for money, clothes and fish.<ref name=\"Risky\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fsm.ac.fj/files/Risky%20Bussiness%20Kiribati-%20HIV%20prevention%20amongst%20women%20who%20board.pdf |title=McMillan K., and H. Worth (2010) Risky Business Kiribati: HIV prevention amongst women who board foreign fishing vessels to sell sex. International HIV Research Group, UNSW, Sydney. |accessdate=2013-06-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030210044/http://www.fsm.ac.fj/files/Risky%20Bussiness%20Kiribati-%20HIV%20prevention%20amongst%20women%20who%20board.pdf |archivedate=October 30, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"CSEC\">Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children (CSEC) and Child Sexual Abuse (CSA) in the Pacific: A Regional Report. (2006). UNICEF Pacific. Retrieved November 24, 2016, from [http://www.unicef.org/eapro/Pacific_CSEC_report.pdf link]</ref>\n\n==Awareness==\nA 2005 news article in [[The Korea Times]] said that, according to [[ECPAT]]-Korea, \"''te korekorea''\" are \"''the best known cases of commercial sexual exploitation of children''\".<!--This information is in the fifth paragraph that starts with \"According to the children's\". The \"children's advocate group\" mentioned in the fifth paragraph is \"ECPAT-Korea\" which is mentioned in the third paragraph and not the \"National Youth Commission\" which is mentioned in the first paragraph. The second, sixth, eighth, ninth and tenth paragraphs mention \"the commission\" which is how the news article refers to the \"National Youth Commission\" after its name was introduced, so the \"children's advocate group\" refers to \"ECPAT-Korea\" of the third paragraph.--><ref name=\"CheongWon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=2665523 |title=Kim, C. (2005). Korean Fishermen Blamed for Child Sex Trade in Kiribati. The Korea Times. |accessdate=2016-11-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927191647/http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/news_view.asp?newsIdx=2665523 |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==Countries involved==\n===Involvement of Kiribati===\nA 2006 news article in [[The Sydney Morning Herald]] said that \"''all Korean fishing boats''\" had been banned by Kiribati from going to Kiribati's ports for a time in 2003 following reports in [[The Korea Herald]] \"''that 30 to 50 girls, mostly under age, were servicing the Korean fishermen.''\"<!--This information is in the fifth paragraph from the bottom that starts with \"He confirms that the situation\".--><ref>Tiniest nations caught in a net. (2006). The Sydney Morning Herald. Retrieved November 25, 2016, from [http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2006/10/08/1160246011151.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap3 link]</ref>\n\nThe KoreKorea issue is being addressed by a Korean institution in collaboration with the Kiribati Government cooperating with the ILO Youth unemployment programme and with the New Zealand\u2019s International Aid and Development Agency (NZAID).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ilo.org/declaration/follow-up/annualreview/archiveofbaselinesbycountry/WCMS_DECL_CL_KIR/lang--en/index.htm |title=Kiribati - Country baselines under the ILO Declaration Annual Review (2000-2008): Effective abolition of child labour \n|publisher=International Labour Organization |date= 15 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Involvement of South Korea===\nA 2005 news article in [[The Korea Times]] said that the National Youth Commission would try to get the \"''Korean fishermen''\" punished as South Korea's \"''anti-juvenile-prostitution law''\" did not allow for \"''sex trade''\".<!--This information is in the third paragraph from the bottom that starts with \"As the anti-juvenile-prostitution\". The \"commission\" mentioned in that paragraph is the \"National Youth Commission\" mentioned in the first paragraph.--><ref name=\"CheongWon\" />\n\n==Mixed children==\nA 2005 news article in [[The Hankyoreh]] said that children had been made from \"''Some''\" \"''KoreKorea''\" and \"''Korean fishermen''\".<ref name=\"Hankyoreh\" />\n\nA 2010 report made by the International HIV Research Group of the [[University of New South Wales]] said that children had been made from \"''a number''\" of ''ainen matawa''\" and \"''Korean seafarers''\", and the report said that the Korean fathers send financial support to these children.<!--This information is in the last sentence of the first paragraph of the right column of numbered page 9 which is the eleventh page of the PDF document.--><ref name=\"Risky\" />\n\n==Men who have sex with ainen matawa==\n===Condom use===\nA document named \"''Synthesis_Kiribati_2013''\"<!--The name of the document can be seen in the end of the URL address as \".../Synthesis_Kiribati_2013.pdf\" and also when a person tries to download the PDF document the default name upon confirming the download is \"Synthesis_Kiribati_2013\".--> on the [[Burnet Institute|Burnet Institute's]] website<!--The Burnet Institute's name and logo is at the bottom of every page of the PDF document and the root of the URL address for the PDF document is \"www.burnet.edu.au/...\".--> said that \"''condom use is intermittent''\" among the \"''ainen matawa''\".<!--The information